00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:40.380
and he did hundreds and hundreds
of icons throughout Egypt.

00:18:40.380 --> 00:18:45.330
They're in churches and
monasteries, and they're beautiful,

00:18:45.330 --> 00:18:49.860 position:56%
and they have their own unique
style, and just, the last time I was

00:18:49.860 --> 00:18:53.240
in Egypt, I was taken
to a church that had --

00:18:53.240 --> 00:18:55.810
it started in the fourth century,

00:18:55.810 --> 00:18:57.950
and it had several
different chapels.

00:18:57.950 --> 00:19:00.120
Each chapel came from
different centuries,

00:19:00.120 --> 00:19:03.170
but they had this incredible
collection

00:19:03.170 --> 00:19:06.670
of icons by Johan the Armenian.

00:19:06.670 --> 00:19:13.720
Coptic iconography was
redefined during the mid-1960s

00:19:13.720 --> 00:19:19.210
by two people -- well, three if
you count the couple, Badour Latif

00:19:19.210 --> 00:19:25.140
and her husband Yussef
Nessif, and Dr. Issac Fanous,

00:19:25.140 --> 00:19:31.730
and in the main cathedral
in Cairo the Badour Latif,

00:19:31.730 --> 00:19:37.220
her icons are in the main
level at the icon stand,

00:19:37.220 --> 00:19:43.070
and Issac Fanous's icons
are in a different level.

00:19:43.070 --> 00:19:46.900
So both of them are very highly
esteemed, and a few years ago,

00:19:46.900 --> 00:19:52.890
I had the really great honor of
meeting Badour Latif at her home,

00:19:52.890 --> 00:19:57.890
and you can see that she's working
on an icon here of St. Mark.

00:19:57.890 --> 00:20:02.210
She died about four years ago,
but it was really a great honor.

00:20:02.210 --> 00:20:05.000
I considered her that
someone who taught me,

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:08.710
even though I never met
her before that point,

00:20:08.710 --> 00:20:14.360
even with the modern Coptic
art, which you see on the right,

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:17.310
you still see the influence
from the past.

00:20:17.310 --> 00:20:24.640
This ancient hymnbook from 1743
showing Moses and the burning bush,

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:32.920
Isaac Fanous did this icon of the
burning bush, and he put St. Mary,

00:20:32.920 --> 00:20:35.910
represented and it,
showing that just

00:20:35.910 --> 00:20:43.100
as the flames did not consume
the burning bush, which was God,

00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:49.190
that St. Mary was not consumed
by having God within her.

00:20:49.190 --> 00:20:52.650
So here we have some
nativity scenes.

00:20:52.650 --> 00:20:55.650
The one of the top left
is by Badour Latif.

00:20:55.650 --> 00:21:01.340
What I always liked about her
art was she has flowers and it.

00:21:01.340 --> 00:21:09.020
She has animals that it,
and just very natural,

00:21:09.020 --> 00:21:11.320
and I always like that.

00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:15.240
I kind of reflect that in my icons.

00:21:15.240 --> 00:21:19.570
Beside hers is a nativity
by Isaac Fanous.

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:21.780
His are very beautiful.

00:21:21.780 --> 00:21:28.330
His or more geometric, and I like
the placement of his figures,

00:21:28.330 --> 00:21:31.680
and so I always try to just kind
of pick out what I like best

00:21:31.680 --> 00:21:37.180
from the two styles and use that.

00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:42.400
Below is one by Johan the
Armenian, and his is more

00:21:42.400 --> 00:21:47.330
of a Byzantine theme,
and then the one I did.

00:21:47.330 --> 00:21:52.910
So now we have, you know, up
into the twentieth century,

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:58.120
and now we're going to talk
about some of my icons.

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:01.290
First of all, something
about the creative process.

00:22:01.290 --> 00:22:05.970
I found this on the Internet,
and yes, whatever span of time,

00:22:05.970 --> 00:22:11.760
let's say I agree a I'm going
to have an icon done by the end

00:22:11.760 --> 00:22:14.910
of the month or within
one month time.

00:22:14.910 --> 00:22:16.880
Okay, work begins.

00:22:16.880 --> 00:22:20.120
My husband, Wafik, will cut
the wood and prepare it,

00:22:20.120 --> 00:22:22.350
and everything's ready to go.

00:22:22.350 --> 00:22:23.650
Okay, yes, I'll do it.

00:22:23.650 --> 00:22:26.040
It'll be ready by the
end of the month.

00:22:26.040 --> 00:22:31.150
The next 25 days, I'm goofing off.

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:33.910
And then a couple days, I
like, yeah, I've really got

00:22:33.910 --> 00:22:39.070
to get started, and all the work
while crying -- and I'm not crying,

00:22:39.070 --> 00:22:41.030
I'm just kind of kicking
myself that, you know,

00:22:41.030 --> 00:22:45.140
I really should've started this
earlier, and the last two days is

00:22:45.140 --> 00:22:46.900
like hurry, hurry, hurry.

00:22:46.900 --> 00:22:50.460
So yes, the creative process.

00:22:50.460 --> 00:22:54.780
So when I get an assignment
for an icon,

00:22:54.780 --> 00:22:58.560
I first draw out a very
rough painting or drawing.

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:02.030
I don't really like to
do a detailed sketch.

00:23:02.030 --> 00:23:03.640
I just -- I don't.

00:23:03.640 --> 00:23:10.250 position:56%
It's a rough drawing, and I work out
placement and everything like that

00:23:10.250 --> 00:23:16.760 position:56%
and what I want written on it, and I
have a few monks who are kind enough

00:23:16.760 --> 00:23:22.480
to look over my Coptic and
make sure spelling is correct,

00:23:22.480 --> 00:23:27.060
make suggestions about
the icon design itself,

00:23:27.060 --> 00:23:28.940
and then I start painting.

00:23:28.940 --> 00:23:34.760
I use acrylic, because it's a paint

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:39.560
that works quickly,
and it dries quickly.

00:23:39.560 --> 00:23:46.500 position:56%
In most iconography, you find people
say that they use the Tempera paint,

00:23:46.500 --> 00:23:51.670
which is with egg white and
pigments and sort of like that,

00:23:51.670 --> 00:23:55.810
but that takes longer
to work with, and monks

00:23:55.810 --> 00:23:59.790
and bishops have told me,
just get the job done.

00:23:59.790 --> 00:24:06.230
So okay. The Coptic art of today,

00:24:06.230 --> 00:24:09.670
it's accepted that the
figures have round heads,

00:24:09.670 --> 00:24:12.350
and again, the large eyes.

00:24:12.350 --> 00:24:16.960
And it's a simple -- it's
not trying for realism.

00:24:16.960 --> 00:24:18.670
It's a style.

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:22.520
It's a simple style, and one thing
about Coptic art which I really,

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:27.920
really enjoy is that the
figures look peaceful,

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:33.620
and it's with the thought that
whatever they have suffered,

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:36.720
even if it's a martyr,
whatever they have suffered,

00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:38.800
the suffering is over.

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:41.920
They're in heaven,
and they're at peace.

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:49.740
So that's one way to always, you
know, recognize a Coptic icon.

00:24:49.740 --> 00:24:52.980
The subject is at peace.

00:24:52.980 --> 00:24:58.440
I recently did a sign for
our church, and again,

00:24:58.440 --> 00:25:05.700
you can see the process
involved, just a crude sketch.

00:25:05.700 --> 00:25:08.880
And I sent it to one of my monk
friends what I wanted to put

00:25:08.880 --> 00:25:12.720
on the sketch, and he
nicely wrote it out for me,

00:25:12.720 --> 00:25:17.560
and whatever the languages, I
always dread doing lettering,

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:20.780
a lot of lettering, because surely,

00:25:20.780 --> 00:25:23.620
I'm going to make a mistake
somewhere, and it's like, oh,

00:25:23.620 --> 00:25:28.890
I left out such and such letter,
and I have to find a way to fix it.

00:25:28.890 --> 00:25:36.070
By the way, one of my main rules of
art is that if you make a mistake,

00:25:36.070 --> 00:25:39.880
and you can't paint over it,
make it part of the design.

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:42.990
So that's happened many times.

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:46.310
This is an icon of St. George.

00:25:46.310 --> 00:25:50.340
You can see where I
roughed in the shadows,

00:25:50.340 --> 00:25:55.390
and then the finished
painting, and with any icon,

00:25:55.390 --> 00:25:59.770
there's going to be several
layers of paint involved.

00:25:59.770 --> 00:26:06.560
Usually with an icon, it's -- you
start out with the dark colors

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:11.750
and you apply the lighter colors,
showing the progress of the soul

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:18.380
from darkness to the light, and
it's nice that acrylic works

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:21.060
out that way, that you
start with the dark,

00:26:21.060 --> 00:26:28.590
and then with gold
leaf, putting that on.

00:26:28.590 --> 00:26:34.410 position:56%
It's a process that depending on the
icon involved, depending on my --

00:26:34.410 --> 00:26:38.610
do I really want to paint
today, which is terrible,

00:26:38.610 --> 00:26:42.960 position:56%
I've done some icons within one day.

00:26:42.960 --> 00:26:46.940
I've done some icons that
just seem to drag on forever.

00:26:46.940 --> 00:26:54.800
So there's no real how long
does it take to do an icon?

00:26:54.800 --> 00:27:01.160
A few years ago, I did altar of a
church, and I worked with the monk.

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:07.150
And he drew out the design that he
wanted, or he told me the design,

00:27:07.150 --> 00:27:11.680
and so you can see in the
middle picture to the right,

00:27:11.680 --> 00:27:15.970
the basic design that became
the central Jesus Christ,

00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:19.660
and you can see there's
elements from the past and it

00:27:19.660 --> 00:27:22.430
like the Angels overhead.

00:27:22.430 --> 00:27:29.340
That's a direct connection to
the ancient image of Jesus,

00:27:29.340 --> 00:27:36.310
the image of Jesus being carried
by angels, and below is Abraham,

00:27:36.310 --> 00:27:43.890
the patriarch, Abraham being given
bread and wine by [inaudible].

00:27:43.890 --> 00:27:48.230
How do you say it?

00:27:48.230 --> 00:27:49.530
Yeah, thank you.

00:27:49.530 --> 00:27:56.430
When I was doing this, looking
at this picture reminds me,

00:27:56.430 --> 00:28:00.250
one of my concerns was
the monk wanted a rainbow.

00:28:00.250 --> 00:28:06.630
This particular altar area
had several angles involved,

00:28:06.630 --> 00:28:12.940
and trying to figure a rainbow
that was going to be even was --

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:16.940
I was measuring here and then
the measure here, go up 2 inches.

00:28:16.940 --> 00:28:19.060
Measure here, go up 2 inches.

00:28:19.060 --> 00:28:21.410
So this monk said, "No-no-no."

00:28:21.410 --> 00:28:25.250
So he found a piece of chalk,
and he taped it to a broomstick,

00:28:25.250 --> 00:28:28.400 position:56%
and he stood, and he drew a rainbow.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:29.900
And it was like, wow.

00:28:29.900 --> 00:28:32.590
Why didn't I think of that?

00:28:32.590 --> 00:28:38.280
And when I was working on the image
of the face of Jesus being held

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:42.860
by the two angels, I was on
a ladder, but it was in front

00:28:42.860 --> 00:28:47.820
of the steps to like
where I'm standing now,

00:28:47.820 --> 00:28:50.010
and it was difficult to reach.

00:28:50.010 --> 00:28:53.400
The ladder was at a difficult
angle, and I'm trying to reach it,

00:28:53.400 --> 00:28:55.670
and the monk was saying,
"But, you know,

00:28:55.670 --> 00:28:58.670
you've got one ear a little
bit lower than the other.

00:28:58.670 --> 00:28:59.970
Can you fix that?"

00:28:59.970 --> 00:29:01.950
So I was trying to get it.

00:29:01.950 --> 00:29:03.600
Again, it was a difficult angle.

00:29:03.600 --> 00:29:06.820
So he said, "Do you mind if
I try, because I'm taller?"

00:29:06.820 --> 00:29:11.540
So he climbed up the ladder,
and he was getting it correct,

00:29:11.540 --> 00:29:15.630
and the young man from
the church came in.

00:29:15.630 --> 00:29:21.680
So he looks at me, and he looks up
at the monk at the ladder painting,

00:29:21.680 --> 00:29:25.620
and he looks back at me like,
so the monk is doing the work.

00:29:25.620 --> 00:29:27.530
What are you doing here?

00:29:27.530 --> 00:29:33.490
And this seraphim, really,

00:29:33.490 --> 00:29:36.480
this is one of my favorite
things I've ever painted.

00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:39.340
I love doing angels,
and so this is just one

00:29:39.340 --> 00:29:44.070
of the favorite things
that I've done.

00:29:44.070 --> 00:29:50.390
This is kind of a, again, different
styles of the entry into Jerusalem.

00:29:50.390 --> 00:29:55.410
The one on the left
is eighteenth-century.

00:29:55.410 --> 00:29:58.240
It's from upper Egypt.

00:29:58.240 --> 00:30:04.100
It's a more simple style, but I
really love this because first

00:30:04.100 --> 00:30:06.780
of all, the dark blue,
but if you look carefully,

00:30:06.780 --> 00:30:11.710
you see the palm leaves in the
background that are being used,

00:30:11.710 --> 00:30:13.430
you know, to welcome Jesus.

00:30:13.430 --> 00:30:19.780
And you see the others throwing
cloths at the feet of Jesus,

00:30:19.780 --> 00:30:25.210
and in this one -- the upper
one done by Fanous, again,

00:30:25.210 --> 00:30:29.950
you see the palm leaves, and you
see the people throwing cloths

00:30:29.950 --> 00:30:33.090
at the feet of Jesus.

00:30:33.090 --> 00:30:35.900
The bottom one is one I did.

00:30:35.900 --> 00:30:41.920
And what I did with the
entry into Jerusalem,

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:44.890
and the disciples are all
wearing the same uniform.

00:30:44.890 --> 00:30:49.680 position:56%
They're wearing white with red, just
so we all know they're disciples,

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:56.050
and all of them except one
has a happy expression.

00:30:56.050 --> 00:30:59.080
One of them, if you look
carefully, is kind of glowering,

00:30:59.080 --> 00:31:01.790
and we all know who he is,

00:31:01.790 --> 00:31:08.440
and all of them are holding a palm
leaf except for one, and also,

00:31:08.440 --> 00:31:12.590
what I do and almost every
entry into Jerusalem,

00:31:12.590 --> 00:31:17.470
and you see that in the
little insert to the left.

00:31:17.470 --> 00:31:23.020
I like to put myself and my
husband, Wafik, into the picture

00:31:23.020 --> 00:31:27.920
that we're watching entry into
Jerusalem, but we're copticized.

00:31:27.920 --> 00:31:33.140
The closest thing about this
one is that she has the long,

00:31:33.140 --> 00:31:37.440
light brown hair, but at least
we're there watching the entry

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:38.740
into Jerusalem.

00:31:38.740 --> 00:31:43.430
This is another one that I
did a couple of years ago.

00:31:43.430 --> 00:31:50.030
It's one of my favorites, and
it's the baby Moses being taken

00:31:50.030 --> 00:31:58.160
from the Nile River, and I was
asked to do this by a Jewish man,

00:31:58.160 --> 00:32:02.350
and so it was fun doing
the ancient temple

00:32:02.350 --> 00:32:07.440
and Miriam hiding in the papyrus.

00:32:07.440 --> 00:32:11.820
Actually, it's on my
list of things to do,

00:32:11.820 --> 00:32:19.290
that someone wants a large painting
of this, and just more temples

00:32:19.290 --> 00:32:20.590
and and so I'm like that.

00:32:20.590 --> 00:32:22.590
So I'm looking forward
to starting that.

00:32:22.590 --> 00:32:25.970
Go through my creative
process again.

00:32:27.860 --> 00:32:29.380
Noah's Ark.

00:32:29.380 --> 00:32:35.170
Basically, this is kind of a
standard, Coptic Noah's Ark.

00:32:35.170 --> 00:32:38.990
As an animal lover, it was
great fun for me to do.

00:32:38.990 --> 00:32:46.310
If you look closely near the
boat, you see a pair of dogs,

00:32:46.310 --> 00:32:48.750
and I have them sitting
down, looking up,

00:32:48.750 --> 00:32:52.250
waiting for their human
friends to come off the boat,

00:32:52.250 --> 00:32:58.030
and then over to the left, there's
two cats, and they're looking

00:32:58.030 --> 00:33:02.550
at the pair of mice that just came
off the boat, and they're thinking,

00:33:02.550 --> 00:33:06.470
should we eat them now or
wait until there's more mice?

00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:12.640
So a monk said to me on this
one, but really, next time,

00:33:12.640 --> 00:33:17.180
you need to keep with
the clean animals.

00:33:17.180 --> 00:33:22.010
And I'm, yeah, sure.

00:33:22.010 --> 00:33:25.600
The icon of the Virgin Mary,
I've gotten into the habit,

00:33:25.600 --> 00:33:31.880
I like to put for stalks of
papyrus and an icon of Jesus

00:33:31.880 --> 00:33:37.130
or the Virgin Mary, because not
only is it a symbol of Egypt,

00:33:37.130 --> 00:33:44.470 position:56%
the earliest known Bible fragments
that exist were on papyrus and found

00:33:44.470 --> 00:33:49.590
in Egypt, and then with the
Virgin Mary, I like to have lotus,

00:33:49.590 --> 00:33:54.900
just a nice flower to remind
her of her time in Egypt.

00:33:54.900 --> 00:34:03.140
Some exceptions to Coptic art
that I do, like if it's a saint

00:34:03.140 --> 00:34:07.120
who has died recently, I mean
within the past 50 years,

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:09.730
where there's photographs
of him, yes,

00:34:09.730 --> 00:34:12.830
I will do a more realistic face.

00:34:12.830 --> 00:34:20.370
The one at the bottom is from
a monastery in upper Egypt,

00:34:20.370 --> 00:34:25.220
and this is a very
unsophisticated painting,

00:34:25.220 --> 00:34:28.410
but I love this icon of this saint.

00:34:28.410 --> 00:34:33.750 position:56%
It might be unsophisticated, but you
can see the painter put his heart

00:34:33.750 --> 00:34:39.500
into it, and so I've made
copies of that icon before,

00:34:39.500 --> 00:34:46.330
and when I was asked to do an
icon of this saint for a church,

00:34:46.330 --> 00:34:51.550
I did a more realistic looking, so
he could look proper next to Jesus,

00:34:51.550 --> 00:34:56.220
but the monk holding
the picture down below,

00:34:56.220 --> 00:34:58.210
he's holding the original icon.

00:34:58.210 --> 00:35:04.200 position:56%
So I could the original icon in,
and a more realistic-looking picture

00:35:04.200 --> 00:35:08.950
of this thing, and these are
just some of my favorite icons.

00:35:08.950 --> 00:35:10.250
I love doing angels.

00:35:10.250 --> 00:35:12.570
Doing the archangels was great fun.

00:35:12.570 --> 00:35:16.220
I call this the family
portrait of archangels.

00:35:16.220 --> 00:35:20.580
The one of Jesus rescuing the lamb.

00:35:20.580 --> 00:35:23.140
Again, as an animal lover, to me,

00:35:23.140 --> 00:35:25.900
this was great fun
on several levels.

00:35:25.900 --> 00:35:30.870
Notice that the lamb, he's caught
in thorns, and he's crying.

00:35:30.870 --> 00:35:36.890
He's so sad, and he feels lost,
and Jesus is coming to rescue him

00:35:36.890 --> 00:35:41.800
and comforting him and saving him.

00:35:41.800 --> 00:35:47.050
And any excuse to do a pretty night
sky, I always enjoy doing that.

00:35:47.050 --> 00:35:51.310
Whether it's the prayer Desimone
or Jesus walking on water.

00:35:51.310 --> 00:35:56.010
And the flight into
Egypt, you can see elements

00:35:56.010 --> 00:35:59.340
from the ancient flight into Egypt.

00:35:59.340 --> 00:36:05.420
So if it's a large icon, I
often lay it flat to work on.

00:36:05.420 --> 00:36:07.940
Some of it has to be
done standing up.

00:36:07.940 --> 00:36:10.260
I can't do a face when
it's laying flat.

00:36:10.260 --> 00:36:11.940
It has to stand up.

00:36:11.940 --> 00:36:14.710
And you can see two of my helpers.

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:18.360
One of them below is
holding the paintbrush,

00:36:18.360 --> 00:36:22.420
and the other one is keeping
the feet of Jesus warm.

00:36:22.420 --> 00:36:28.340
These two icons were going
to a church in Pennsylvania.

00:36:28.340 --> 00:36:31.520
I thought I was finished
with them the night before.

00:36:31.520 --> 00:36:34.240
We were going to transport them.

00:36:34.240 --> 00:36:38.570
And then I tore the gold leaf

00:36:38.570 --> 00:36:41.850
under the inscription,
the Coptic inscription.

00:36:41.850 --> 00:36:43.150
I tore the gold leaf.

00:36:43.150 --> 00:36:44.780
I tried to repair it.

00:36:44.780 --> 00:36:46.730 position:56%
It looked like it had been repaired.

00:36:46.730 --> 00:36:48.030
I tried a different way.

00:36:48.030 --> 00:36:50.250 position:56%
It looked like it had been repaired.

00:36:50.250 --> 00:36:54.380
So I ended up painting an Angel --

00:36:54.380 --> 00:36:56.210
but if I paint the
angel on one side,

00:36:56.210 --> 00:36:59.340
it's going to have to
be on the other side.

00:36:59.340 --> 00:37:03.520
Now if it's on one icon, it's going
to have to be on the other icon.

00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:08.220
So I was up until like 6
o'clock painting little angels

00:37:08.220 --> 00:37:10.490
on these icons and varnishing them.

00:37:10.490 --> 00:37:18.440
I finished that icon at six in
the morning, last coat of varnish,

00:37:18.440 --> 00:37:24.540 position:56%
and we got up like at seven or eight
to load them up and transport them.

00:37:24.540 --> 00:37:27.550
And it's not the first time
I'm letting the varnish dry

00:37:27.550 --> 00:37:30.280
as we're carrying it
out to a trailer.

00:37:30.280 --> 00:37:35.990
And then I have my other helper,
my husband Wafik, and what he does,

00:37:35.990 --> 00:37:40.310
he cuts the wood to size,
and he prepares the word.

00:37:40.310 --> 00:37:44.200
He gives of the primary
coats of white paint,

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:48.770
then he also makes
a lot of the frames.

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:56.340
What we see here is at a show that
was all the Orthodox churches,

00:37:56.340 --> 00:37:58.830
the icons from all
the Orthodox churches.

00:37:58.830 --> 00:38:02.330
They asked me if I would
demonstrate painting icon.

00:38:02.330 --> 00:38:04.390
I had one just about
finished anyway.

00:38:04.390 --> 00:38:08.010
So I brought that, and
they put me up on a stage,

00:38:08.010 --> 00:38:12.200
and as I stood there painting,
a couple people walked by

00:38:12.200 --> 00:38:14.680
and said, "Oh, nice icon.

00:38:14.680 --> 00:38:16.320
Yeah, okay."

00:38:16.320 --> 00:38:18.830
So after a while, I said
to my husband, well,

00:38:18.830 --> 00:38:21.120
I'm going to go get
something to drink.

00:38:21.120 --> 00:38:25.720
If you want to do something,
just take the paint and on each

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:29.390
of these white dots
put another white dot.

00:38:29.390 --> 00:38:32.600
It's representing the
stars of heaven.

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:34.650
So he's doing that.

00:38:34.650 --> 00:38:35.980
I go get a drink.

00:38:35.980 --> 00:38:41.010
I come back, and there's like about
30 people crowded around the stage,

00:38:41.010 --> 00:38:44.540
and they're doing like,
wow, what an artist!

00:38:44.540 --> 00:38:46.560
What a beautiful icon!

00:38:46.560 --> 00:38:49.000
And you know, he's standing there.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:52.650
All he needed was a beret.

00:38:52.650 --> 00:38:58.250
A beret. And so that was -- so
I just sat there entry I Coke

00:38:58.250 --> 00:38:59.830
and let him be the great artist.

00:38:59.830 --> 00:39:06.230
And the other one he was -- I was
doing this icon that was going

00:39:06.230 --> 00:39:11.000
to be traveling to Egypt within the
next couple of days, and so he gets

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:12.590
up at 4 o'clock to go to work,

00:39:12.590 --> 00:39:14.210
and his soon as he
walks into the kitchen.

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:16.770
I've been up all night
working on the icon.

00:39:16.770 --> 00:39:18.070
He comes into the kitchen.

00:39:18.070 --> 00:39:19.880
I'm, Wafik, you've got
to write this in Arabic.

00:39:19.880 --> 00:39:21.750
"I just woke up."

00:39:21.750 --> 00:39:23.050
I'm, no, no.

00:39:23.050 --> 00:39:24.810
Come on. It won't take -- come on.

00:39:24.810 --> 00:39:28.390
So he was very nice to
put the Arabic on that

00:39:28.390 --> 00:39:31.320
at 4 o'clock in the morning.

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:34.890
We went to Jerusalem a
couple of months ago,

00:39:34.890 --> 00:39:41.310
and we went to a monastery
in Jericho that was named

00:39:41.310 --> 00:39:44.390
for the Zaccheus, who was
in the tree that Jesus said

00:39:44.390 --> 00:39:46.900
to him, "Zaccheus, come down."

00:39:46.900 --> 00:39:50.030
And this small Coptic monastery,

00:39:50.030 --> 00:39:54.930
all of the icons were the Coptic
style except one which was in front

00:39:54.930 --> 00:39:59.750
of the candle stand, and
that was a European print

00:39:59.750 --> 00:40:03.040
of the scene of Jesus and Zaccheus.

00:40:03.040 --> 00:40:08.500
And so monk said, "I really wish I
could get a Coptic icon of that."

00:40:08.500 --> 00:40:10.570
And I said, I wish I
could do it to you,

00:40:10.570 --> 00:40:14.200
but I don't know how
I would get it to you.

00:40:14.200 --> 00:40:20.080
So we went back to Jerusalem, and I
was telling the hotel manager that,

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:25.200
you know, if only, and he said
tell me the size wood you need,

00:40:25.200 --> 00:40:27.800
and of course, it has to
the high-grade plywood.

00:40:27.800 --> 00:40:32.020
Not just regular plywood
high-grade plywood, and so he said,

00:40:32.020 --> 00:40:35.180
"I'll get it for you,"
and the desk clerk said,

00:40:35.180 --> 00:40:39.620
"I'll find you nearby art store
where you can buy the paints."

00:40:39.620 --> 00:40:48.440
So within two days I did a Coptic
Zaccheus, and I signed their names

00:40:48.440 --> 00:40:52.430
on the icon also that I
had an assist from them.

00:40:52.430 --> 00:40:55.730
And by the way, I signed Wafik's
name on all my icons, too,

00:40:55.730 --> 00:41:01.420 position:56%
because really and truly, I
wouldn't be doing icons without him.

00:41:01.420 --> 00:41:06.050
Not only does he cut the wood and
prepare it and stuff like that,

00:41:06.050 --> 00:41:10.890
but when I'm doing my last-minute
rush and just all day on painting,

00:41:10.890 --> 00:41:16.770 position:56%
all night I'm painting, he's really,
okay, he does so he comes home

00:41:16.770 --> 00:41:18.410
after a long day of work.

00:41:18.410 --> 00:41:19.710
He does the dinner.

00:41:19.710 --> 00:41:21.010
He does the housecleaning.

00:41:21.010 --> 00:41:22.310
Just get the icon done.

00:41:22.310 --> 00:41:23.610
Get the icon done.

00:41:23.610 --> 00:41:27.920
So he deserves a place
on the icon too.

00:41:27.920 --> 00:41:32.740
Don't expect such niceness
out of me on a regular basis.

00:41:33.940 --> 00:41:40.830
This is, I went to a large
family conference of a church

00:41:40.830 --> 00:41:43.570
in Connecticut, and
they had a bishop there

00:41:43.570 --> 00:41:45.450
that I worked with him before.

00:41:45.450 --> 00:41:48.740
And he called me just before
we got there, and he said,

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:51.650
"We need two icons
of the resurrection."

00:41:51.650 --> 00:41:55.200
And I said, oh no,
no one told me that.

00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:59.920
He said, "Can you do two icons by
Sunday so I can consecrate them?"

00:41:59.920 --> 00:42:05.330
Okay, so in two days I did
two icons of the resurrection,

00:42:05.330 --> 00:42:12.650
and this is him consecrating
them, and my priest here,

00:42:12.650 --> 00:42:14.870
Father Chanute [assumed spelling],
please don't get any ideas

00:42:14.870 --> 00:42:17.960
to ask me can you do to
icons within two days.

00:42:17.960 --> 00:42:27.380 position:56%
No. This the icon that I did of a
saint who was recently made or named

00:42:27.380 --> 00:42:35.500
by our church, and this bishop
had asked me to do this icon.

00:42:35.500 --> 00:42:39.200
The body of this saint
is in his church.

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:43.410
So he took the icon
with him to Egypt,

00:42:43.410 --> 00:42:47.620
and you see him consecrating it.

00:42:47.620 --> 00:42:54.060
An icon is either on the walls
the church or they're also used

00:42:54.060 --> 00:42:57.090
in zeffas, which is a procession

00:42:57.090 --> 00:43:00.070
around the church in
honor of a saint.

00:43:00.070 --> 00:43:05.550
Like if we have relics of a
saint, then on the anniversary

00:43:05.550 --> 00:43:11.790
of that saint, we take the relics
around after they're anointed

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:16.060
with holy oil, and the
icons go around with them.

00:43:16.060 --> 00:43:21.120
So to me, it's really a
great pleasure to contribute

00:43:21.120 --> 00:43:24.770
to the honoring of a saint.

00:43:24.770 --> 00:43:27.750
I've got to say that
when working on an icon,

00:43:27.750 --> 00:43:31.780
you really do feel a certain
closeness to the saint.

00:43:31.780 --> 00:43:35.170
It's really hard to
describe, but you do feel,

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:40.460
if not in actual communication,
it's a closeness,

00:43:40.460 --> 00:43:44.500
and it's a really,
really nice feeling.

00:43:44.500 --> 00:43:47.050
One of the things I really
like about Coptic art,

00:43:47.050 --> 00:43:51.550
especially the Coptic Last Supper,
is that instead of a table full

00:43:51.550 --> 00:43:57.340
of food, the table has two things
on it, the wine and the bread,

00:43:57.340 --> 00:43:59.770
which will become the
body and blood.

00:43:59.770 --> 00:44:02.990
The whole thing is
about the communion.

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:06.500
Leonardo da Vinci has
the famous Last Supper

00:44:06.500 --> 00:44:08.290
where the table is full of food.

00:44:08.290 --> 00:44:12.590
There's up plate full of
lemon slices and everything,

00:44:12.590 --> 00:44:14.820
and the message gets lost.

00:44:14.820 --> 00:44:17.440
But the Coptic art, it's basic.

00:44:17.440 --> 00:44:20.480
It's the blood in the body.

00:44:20.480 --> 00:44:25.720
The ancient icon of this to
the right, it's not Coptic.

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:31.240 position:56%
It's actually Syrian, but I loved it
so much I wanted to show it to you.

00:44:31.240 --> 00:44:36.390
It's looking down from the point
of view of God, and it first,

00:44:36.390 --> 00:44:40.740
you see a table with maybe
a leg of lamb in the middle

00:44:40.740 --> 00:44:44.380
for the Passover meal, but I
read an interpretation of it.

00:44:44.380 --> 00:44:46.860
It's actually the communion cup.

00:44:46.860 --> 00:44:49.390
The whole table is
the communion cup.

00:44:49.390 --> 00:44:53.260
Jesus pointing at it
saying drink this.

00:44:53.260 --> 00:45:01.240
So the whole thing is a cup, and
is being offered to the viewer.

00:45:01.240 --> 00:45:05.700
While we were in Israel, we
saw the Mount of Temptation,

00:45:05.700 --> 00:45:08.560
which I thought was really
neat, and next time I do an icon

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:13.650
of the Temptation of Christ,
that will be utilized.

00:45:13.650 --> 00:45:18.560
In this one that I did, I put,
because of the Bible verse,

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:23.230
"And he showed them the cities
as if in a moment of time."

00:45:23.230 --> 00:45:27.220
I put various cities,
Athens and Rome.

00:45:27.220 --> 00:45:32.240
I even put Washington DC,
because this is a moment in time,

00:45:32.240 --> 00:45:37.230
and so that was a fun icon to do.

00:45:37.230 --> 00:45:39.900
Different angels from
different times.

00:45:39.900 --> 00:45:42.620
Minus the one on the right.

00:45:42.620 --> 00:45:44.590
Again, you see the
beauty of Coptic art.

00:45:44.590 --> 00:45:48.480
Not just the modern Coptic art,
but the ancient Coptic art,

00:45:48.480 --> 00:45:50.710
and to me it's just so beautiful.

00:45:50.710 --> 00:45:55.720
I just feel that Coptic
churches here, in Egypt,

00:45:55.720 --> 00:45:58.330
everywhere there's a Coptic
church, they really need

00:45:58.330 --> 00:46:01.240
to embrace their heritage.

00:46:02.310 --> 00:46:05.820
So right now, well,
actually there's more pieces

00:46:05.820 --> 00:46:07.210
of wood sitting there now.

00:46:07.210 --> 00:46:09.370
This is my living room.

00:46:09.370 --> 00:46:14.500
The big icon is like 8 feet across,

00:46:14.500 --> 00:46:17.460
and then there's other icons
there in various stages.

00:46:17.460 --> 00:46:18.760
I have more.

00:46:18.760 --> 00:46:20.560
Wafik just keeps bringing
them out saying, "Here,

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:22.660
and this one is for so-and-so."

00:46:22.660 --> 00:46:27.550
And this is what doing
icons is all about.

00:46:27.550 --> 00:46:29.800
It's putting you in touch with God.

00:46:29.800 --> 00:46:36.700
It's a window into heaven, and it's
really a great honor and privilege

00:46:36.700 --> 00:46:39.780
and blessing to me
that I can do this.

00:46:39.780 --> 00:46:46.690
That hopefully, I can get people
to look at an icon and tell a story

00:46:46.690 --> 00:46:50.690
and make them want to
be in touch with God.

00:46:50.690 --> 00:46:56.510
And that's my story of being an
iconographer in the Coptic church.

