&gt;&gt; I'm someone who can
only draw stick figures,

00:47:12.310 --> 00:47:23.640
and I take my [inaudible],
but I studied art history.

00:47:23.640 --> 00:47:29.130
So wonder if you could tell us
is the cart before the horse

00:47:29.130 --> 00:47:31.210
of where you studied art?

00:47:31.210 --> 00:47:33.940
Was it after you got
fascinated with icons?

00:47:33.940 --> 00:47:37.330
&gt;&gt;Evelyn Rophael: I've always done
art in one form or another, yes.

00:47:37.330 --> 00:47:38.690
I've always loved icons.

00:47:38.690 --> 00:47:41.870
I only knew Greek icons, you
know, until I went to Egypt,

00:47:41.870 --> 00:47:45.750 position:56%
but once I went to Egypt and started
looking at their icons it was just,

00:47:45.750 --> 00:47:47.050
you know, I've got to try this.

00:47:47.050 --> 00:47:50.470
I did not have a formal study
except that I really threw myself

00:47:50.470 --> 00:47:52.810
into studying what
is it about this icon

00:47:52.810 --> 00:47:57.110
that not only is telling the
story, but what do I like about it

00:47:57.110 --> 00:48:00.400 position:56%
that I can translate into what I do?

00:48:00.400 --> 00:48:04.230
Like the one icon I was
pointing out that she likes

00:48:04.230 --> 00:48:06.870
to put flowers in them in animals.

00:48:06.870 --> 00:48:11.090
And I really like putting nature
in there, and when I was talking

00:48:11.090 --> 00:48:14.050
to this iconographer
about, oh, you know,

00:48:14.050 --> 00:48:16.950
I love the way you have the animals
smiling and something like that.

00:48:16.950 --> 00:48:19.630
She said, "You know, that's
just what the Pope said to me."

00:48:19.630 --> 00:48:21.510
So.

00:48:21.510 --> 00:48:26.040
